\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Commentary
\emph default
.
 It didn't initially seem to me like this should exist.
 My intuitive example for a linear-algebraically 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nice
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subset that isn't a linear subspace is an affine subspace that doesn't
 contain zero, but closure under addition and inverses says that if 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $v+(-v)=0\in U$
\end_inset

.
 How else could something so 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nice
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (closure under addition and inverses) fail to be a subspace?
\end_layout

